ion it was my face that burned and my bells that went silent for a day, and I have not forgiven that silence. If you must expose the method, do it in a way that teaches and repairs rather than delights the crowd with a villain and a flogging, because markets remember humiliation longer than they remember heroism. I will admit the bellweights ran light on festival days by a fraction we called kindness, and I will agree to fix them in public if the compact binds all parties to their own corrections. Let us try double signatures in chalk and oil, a singer from the looms to set the rhythm of seals, and a pilot's lead dipped in tallow on random lots to taste the truth of the bricks before they are stacked. Give me a safeguard that strengthens trust and I will open the vault so you can show the city how the honest bricks sound when struck by a clear hand.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Lysa Quill\", \"lines\": \"I have drafted the first paragraph to read that the oath-chart shall be a public instrument lodged under the Lantern Archive's perpetual flame, cross-referenced by the Exchange's witness circle, and sung into memory by the Loom Cathedral on Fogfast. The second paragraph names the Pilots as stewards of current marks with a duty to revise under sworn notice, and it names the Order as auditors of intention with a duty to call a fast when greed oversteps measure. The third binds House Verrin's outfitting claims to emergencies declared by a triple bell of Protector, Hall, and Order, with a sunset clause at the next high river so that efficiency does not grow a throne. A fourth describes the counterfeit's method in sterile terms without a culprit, then prescribes safeguards of weight, song, and sample that any stallholder can verify without a learned scribe. If there are objections, I ask that we speak them here where the bells can record our breath, because sloppy law is the quickest sand known to any city that bargains with water.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Ring the bell of confession\", \"text\": \"Kezra stands within the sand circle until the bells hush, then speaks into the quiet with the steadiness that pilots use on bends where they cannot see the far shore. They describe the winter when a healer's bill outpaced mercy, and the small route sold in a back alley to a smiling broker with clean hands and a watchful shadow. There is no embellishment and no excuse, only the naming of the price and the naming of the regret that followed like a lantern that would not be doused. Kezra asks the Hall to let that thread end here, cut publicly, and offers a thorn on the tongue to bind the promise that no such sale will be made again under any pressure short of a life in the room. They then turn the confession into a bridge, asking all present to commit a fault of their own to the oath-chart as a first weight, so that the chart starts with truths that sting and not with boasts that float.\", \"outcome\": \"The Order stiffens and then nods as the thorn pricks and the taste of iron proves the vow, and Ansel publicly names the act forgiven when tied to a stronger promise. The Pilots murmur approval because a clear line is better than a pretty lie, and Olan offers his own admission about a wage argument lost in pride to match the weight. The Night Cartographers step back from their leverage because a thread cut in the open cannot be tugged in the dark, though their silent eyes promise they will watch for new threads to tie. Sera Verrin smiles that thin merchant's smile that says both respect and calculation, and while she does not praise the confession, she chooses not to weaponize it, banking the public's taste for courage as coin she can spend later. The bells record the confession as a clean tone, and the city's rumor mill carries the story as a hard truth rather than gossip, strengthening the ground for the tri-fold compact to be signed without whispers undermining every clause.\"},\n        {\