 blood on the floor.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C3\", \"title\": \"Amend the Verrin charter with emergency gate-clauses\", \"text\": \"Kezra holds Sera's parchment up to the lantern and reads it aloud as if it were a route in fog, naming the places where it runs straight and the shoals where a private keel would scrape public trust. They propose a gate of three bells that must be rung together before House Verrin can claim outfitter authority: the Protector's necessity, the Hall's solvency, and the Order's mercy, each bell a hand on a single rope. The authority is granted for emergencies only, sunsets at the next floodmark, and is recorded on the oath-chart so that any citizen can see when the harness tightens and when it must be loosed. Verrin wagons are welcomed to carry weight when the river runs thin or the moths fall silent, but every crate's seal is mirrored in the Archive, and any thumb on any scale will sour the ink and sing the bells. In exchange, the city accepts Sera's discipline where it serves all and not just the manse on the terrace, and Kezra names the compact as the table where this bargain eats and is watched.\", \"outcome\": \"Sera hesitates, calculates, and then nods with a courtly tilt because a bound authority is still authority, and public bells can be taught to ring when asked if the asking is honest. The Pilots relax because their routes remain public and their hands on the chart stay steady, and Olan signals that the Brotherhood will not boycott a house that has accepted visible checks on its reach. The Spindlewrights approve because a sunset clause keeps silk from being yoked forever, and Brynna remarks that harnesses do less harm when the skin they're on knows when it will be free. The Order signs the clause because it makes emergency power answer to mercy as well as measure, and Ansel adds a line that requires vows to be read aloud before any such authority is used. The charter survives in amended form, Sera earns a grudging courtesy rather